How to compile and run:
To compile, use "make typewriter". To run, use the command 
./typewriter, followed by a text file that may or may not exist,
and optionally, a file to take in the log movements of the cursor and
state of the text. Without the third argument, the updates will not be
recorded. Additionally, if the second argument is a valid file, it 
should display the contents of that file to fit the bounds of the
terminal. Conversely, if the file does not exist, the typewriter
program will create the file in the directory. 

Outline of ADT (architectural overview):
In the Editor class, I used a vector of strings to represent the text. I
decided to use a vector of strings to contain the printable characters
and the amount of rows in the function. Specifically, in order to render, I
would have to access every element in the vector, making it the most amount
of sense to use a vector to have fast access to any element. Additionally, in
the Editor class, I have also included two ActionStacks in my program, one for
redoes and another for undoes. Within the ActionStacks, I have used a list. 
I decided to use a list because to make an implementation of a stack, I would
need fast access to the last element of a queue. In the C++ version of a list,
there is relatively fast access to the last element, along with removal and
ability to append to the end of that element. This is because of the use of a 
back pointer. 

Testing:
Within the files I have submitted, I have included 7 input files that I have 
used to test the outputs of the_better_typewriter and my implementation of
typewriter. Additionally, I have included an unit_test to test all of the
relevant functions in ActionStack. Of the 7 input files, the second test was
to test the arrowkey functions, and the seventh was to test the undo and redo
functions. The other input files contain tests designed to cause newline and
wraparound exceptions. 

